<Folder id="folderRow11"><name><![CDATA[Text (#1)]]></name><Placemark id="p11"><name><![CDATA[Sample (#1)]]></name><snippet></snippet><description></description><styleUrl>#style_Template1</styleUrl><ExtendedData><Data name="Title"><value><![CDATA[Sample Balloon with Text]]></value></Data><Data name="Subtitle"><value><![CDATA[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]]></value></Data><Data name="Paragraph1_Text"><value><![CDATA[The U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum is a living memorial, dedicated to honoring the victims of the Holocaust. One vital way it fulfills this mission is by confronting threats of genocide and related crimes against humanity today.]]></value></Data><Data name="Paragraph2_Text"><value><![CDATA[When Google Earth was first released in June 2005, the Museum's Academy for Genocide Prevention was exploring how foreign policy professionals could better share information about emerging threats of genocide and mass atrocities. The Museum recognized Google Earth's potential to help organize and present information in a compelling and timely way, and to serve as an effective vehicle for public outreach and education about genocide and related crimes against humanity.]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_URL"><value><![CDATA[http://www.google.com/earth/outreach/stories/darfur.html]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_Text"><value><![CDATA[Crisis In Darfur - Case Study]]></value></Data></ExtendedData><Point><coordinates>-122.497677,37.7656661</coordinates></Point></Placemark>

<Folder id="folderRow13"><name><![CDATA[Text and Logo (#2)]]></name><Placemark id="p13"><name><![CDATA[Sample (#2)]]></name><snippet></snippet><description></description><styleUrl>#style_Template2</styleUrl><ExtendedData><Data name="Title"><value><![CDATA[Sample Balloon - Text & Logo]]></value></Data><Data name="Subtitle"><value><![CDATA[Architecture for Humanity]]></value></Data><Data name="Paragraph_1_Text"><value><![CDATA[Architecture for Humanity is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization that seeks architectural solutions to humanitarian crisis and brings design services to communities in need. Our design team relies on Google SketchUp software for the intuitive and efficient interface to develop architectural designs and model the details of a project for local contractors.]]></value></Data><Data name="Paragraph_2_Text"><value><![CDATA[Because Architecture for Humanity engages a diverse range of projects around the world, each project manager and design fellow finds new and creative ways of working with Google SketchUp.]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_URL"><value><![CDATA[http://www.google.com/earth/outreach/stories/architectureforhumanity.html]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_Text"><value><![CDATA[Case Study Link]]></value></Data></ExtendedData><Point><coordinates>-122.449601,37.7932882</coordinates></Point></Placemark>

<Folder id="folderRow15"><name><![CDATA[Image and Text (#3)]]></name><Placemark id="p15"><name><![CDATA[Sample (#3)]]></name><snippet></snippet><description></description><styleUrl>#style_Template3</styleUrl><ExtendedData><Data name="Title"><value><![CDATA[Sample Balloon - Image & Text]]></value></Data><Data name="Image_URL"><value><![CDATA[http://www.google.com/earth/outreach/images/stories_halo1.jpg]]></value></Data><Data name="Image_Width"><value><![CDATA[480]]></value></Data><Data name="Image_Height"><value><![CDATA[320]]></value></Data><Data name="Paragraph_Text"><value><![CDATA[With the mission of "getting mines out of the ground, now," The HALO Trust is the world's oldest, largest and most successful humanitarian landmine clearance agency, having cleared more than 13 million landmines and other explosive remnants of war. Today, HALO has over 8,000 locally recruited staff. We invest in local leadership, keeping affected communities integral to the process and providing employment in areas that offer few opportunities. HALO uses Google Earth for minefield survey (the process of identifying and mapping mined areas), data validation and to produce maps for donors, governments, and other NGOs.]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_URL"><value><![CDATA[http://www.google.com/earth/outreach/stories/halo.html]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_Text"><value><![CDATA[Halo Trust Case Study]]></value></Data></ExtendedData><Point><coordinates>-122.401529,37.7656661</coordinates></Point></Placemark>

<Folder id="folderRow17"><name><![CDATA[Image Text Logo (#4)]]></name><Placemark id="p17"><name><![CDATA[Sample (#4)]]></name><snippet></snippet><description></description><styleUrl>#style_Template4</styleUrl><ExtendedData><Data name="Title"><value><![CDATA[Sample with Image, Text & Logo]]></value></Data><Data name="Image_URL"><value><![CDATA[http://www.google.com/earth/outreach/images/stories_unep2.jpg]]></value></Data><Data name="Image_Width"><value><![CDATA[384]]></value></Data><Data name="Image_Height"><value><![CDATA[252]]></value></Data><Data name="Paragraph_Text"><value><![CDATA[The principal mandate of the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) is to monitor the world environmental situation to ensure that emerging environmental problems of wide international significance receive appropriate and adequate consideration by governments.  A UNEP publication One Planet, Many People; Atlas of Our Changing Environment was released at the World Environment Day ceremonies in June, 2005 and has been updated regularly since that time with satellite images of environmental hot spots around the world. Subsequently, UNEP made the Atlas photos and text available on the Internet at www.uneplive.org]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_URL"><value><![CDATA[http://www.google.com/earth/outreach/stories/unep.html]]></value></Data><Data name="Link_Text"><value><![CDATA[UNEP Case Study]]></value></Data></ExtendedData><Point><coordinates>-122.419907,37.7209943</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
